The Tundra I is a model rocket designed for flight with an Estes C11 or D engine. The rocket is fairly small in size and designed to be lightweight for maximum altitude. Although there is nothing build in yet for parachute deployment, it can be easily rigged to do so. To hold the rocket in place, use a metal wire and create a j shape at its bottom and fold it perpendicular to the rest of the wire (assuming the rest is straight). This will help to hold the engine in. The rocket has yet to be tested but is going under manufacturing as of now for testing. Happy launching!

Make sure that when printing you have the payload housing flipped upside down (thinner tube away from the build plate) for maximum stability and to have the motor housing facing the same way as if the rocket were to be launched (relative to the build plate). The nose cone should have the flat side faced towards the build plate and  may need support material to print properly.

description.text:
A friends walks in my shop and grabs my Harbor Freight flashlight and says this needs a belt clip, so I made one. Sometimes you just need the right seed. I added a clip design that will hold the same 15mm magnet as my tubing cutter. Now I have to buy one of the new red triangle flashlights and see if a clip makes sense for that model.

I did find that older/newer modules of the flashlight use either wood type screws in plastic or 3 millimeter threaded screws in inserts. I had to use longer screws to make it through the clip anyway, since the screws in the flashlight are recessed and to engage the inserts. I used 12mm length 3mm threaded screws that worked well in the inserts and they actually re-tapped the plastic in the flashlights that didn't have inserts. I took a picture of the two different screws that I removed from the flashlights as a reference.

I created this project for me to improve my soldering as well as my electronics and CAD skills.
I just used the parts I had laying around thus the parts used might be noght the right for this job but it works for me.

I also use just one of the charging controller's LEDs because I broke away a solder pad for the other LED.

title: Motor shaft 5mm to 8mm Threaded Rod Coupling (13mm hex nut)

description.text:
Actually I designed this for my DIY CNC, but since this uses 5mm motor shafts and 8mm threaded rods, like many 3D printers do, maybe someone can use it for his printer.

Put two M8 hex nuts (DIN934) on the rod, seperated by a 8,4mm washer (DIN125) and fasten them tight. The washer fits into the inner notch, hence the threaded rod has no chance to move out of the part.

The parts diameter is smaller in the center on purpose, to provide a little flexibility.

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

~ 25-30%

Notes:

I printed the part with 4 perimeters to improve the strength.
Supports needed on the hex nut side. 5mm shaft side printed well without supports.

The first thing to do is to print the parts, and get the other hardware together.

You will need:

  • Wire for the nose ring (I used stainless lock wire)
  • Lead for the keel weight. You can use a sinker, or any lead really, bash it into shape. This needs to weigh around 4 grams.
  • Barb crown for the tail. You can either cut up a small pencil jig, or get a new set of barbs.
    The best I've found are Harimitsu brand, you can get these here: http://www.fishonproshop.com.au/fishonproshop/SelectProd.do?prodId=657

The parts go together like this.

Glue the two halves together, with the nose ring and lead keel in place. Leave the barbs out for now, you can put them in later.

Have fun with masking out the lure and painting it. Ensure that you sand the layer lines off before painting.

Glue the eyes in after painting. I print the eyes in black filament, so that there is less to paint. You can use whatever colour you like, obviously.

After painting, you can cover the lure in a layer of clear epoxy. Keeping the lure rotating for a couple of hours can keep the coat more even, and eliminate drips. This is a simple setup to keep the lure rotating while the glue cures.

Finally, glue in some feathers and the barb at the back, and you're ready to catch some squid!

description.text:
UPDATE
This hotend assembly has mounts for three different mounting schemes for either a clone or genuine E3D hotend
.

  1. Typical hotend w/ only BLTouch or Induction sensor
  2. Precision Piezo sensor
  3. Zesty Nimble w/ Precision Piezo sensor

This assembly was designed to provide a compact and simple hotend mount for the Hypercube Evolution.

My design goals were to give an option to use the original x-carriage mount designed by SCOTT_3D with the choice to use the modified version. I incorporated several options to use either an inductive probe (12mm), or BLTouch. I am working on a design to utilize the Percision Piezo, and will upload when finished. I don't use mesh leveling, so if there are issues with these designs, please let me know. The fan mount and duct was inspired by jcen517.

I included 2 options for electrical connections on the hotend mount based on how many wires are required for your setup. The connectors used are MPX. The hotend I use is a clone, so if it doesn't fit well, I can make the modifications.

Lastly, I designed a duct which wraps around the hotend and maintains a fairly even pressure at the outlets. There are three outlets at the bottom. The idea behind the flow was to give each side 40% and the center 20% by using ribs in the duct which divide the airflow initially entering the horizontal portion of the duct. I also added a rib in the center since initially the flow was skewed to one side of the duct for the center outlet.

I will upload printed versions I am currently using when I get more time.

Updates:

20171111: Added version of duct whereby two exit ports are pointed towards the nozzle.

20171120: Precision Piezo mount with two extruder mount options for either an embedded bowden connector or the typical clones with a PC4-01 (Thread Diameter:9.729mm). If requested, I can remove the connector in the center if only two connectors are required. The clone or original E3D hotend heatsinks fit the PP Hotend Mount 1.0 design.

I printed the hotend mount in PETG, 0.15 layer height, 4 top and bottom layers, 3 walls, 0.4 mm hotend diameter, and 40% infill. The extruder mount was printed the same as above with 0.24 layer height.

I don't have the Precision Piezo kit yet to test, but I printed everything and it should work. If you have a sensor, and want to try it out before I receive mine, please let me know if there are any issues.

20171121: Updated the fan mounts due to the material being too thin in the corners. I made the adjustment just prior to initially uploading, then re-checked today and it was too thin, so made the modifications.

20180128: Tested and modified the parts for the Precision Piezo (PP) sensor.

The performance from generating 10 sets of bilinear grid mesh data achieved a calculated range (accuracy) of 0.0256 mm or 25.6 um and standard deviation of 0.0076 mm or 7.6 um. This test was most representative of results when executing a bed level prior to starting a print. Moreover, it is noteworthy to mention here that the kinematics of each machine will play a significant role in the grid mesh accuracy. The repeatability tests yielded a calculated range (accuracy) of 0.0036 mm or 3.6 um and standard deviation of 0.0013 mm or 1.3 um. Since this machine has a z-axis that is driven by a trapezoidal leadscrew and the probe is striking the same point, this test typically yields more favorable results.

See the test results in the files section for more information. I also removed the previous STLs to remove confusion. If someone needs them, please let me know.

20180217: Designed a mount for the Zesty Nimble that incorporates the Precision Piezo sensor. This mount was designed with the help of Chris Branson who printed, evaluated, and provided feedback to improve the design.

The Precision Piezo files are updated to mount the Piezo20 PCB for the Piezo20 Module in the front of the extruder mount. There are also STL files to mount a Universal Piezo Z-Probe PCB for the Piezo20 Module on the left side as viewed from behind the extruder mount.

There is a STL Information Section added below that explains each STL in further detail and a PDF file in the files section for download.

The screw cannot take a lot of torque so use a pair of pliers to support the shaft as you initiate the first few turns. After it is broken in, it should work fine.

title: LWC / 3D IN  collaboration "FalaX"  custom pistol crossbow
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
UPDATE 03.11.2017 There will be no building video, I am making a picture by picture HOWTO you can directly watch in the Thing Gallery. I think this is even better than a video.
I will make a short video, but its only about how you can make the needed Spring for the Trigger mechanism!

3D IN meets LWC and turns the "Falcon" pistol crossbow into the " FalaX"

This crossbow from 3d IN ( https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2056714) comes with a no derivations license, so normally nobody is allowed to alter and re-share the design. I had a nice talk with William, the man behind 3D IN, he is a very friendly person and a true genius when it comes to 3d engineering, His profile says " intermidiate" but I can certainly tell you he is more a proffessional!

His original Crossbow Design functions like a dream, it is toy grade with not a lot of power, perfect for kids to play with or some work office fights XD But what if we could crank up the power by quite a bit?! Well I did that and William was so kind to allow me to re-share the modified parts!!! Thats is so freaking awesome!!! At this point I want to thank William from 3D IN once again for giving me permission to do so ;)

The modified version features a small picatinny rail on top for a tactical laser or small holo/reddot sight.

A long piccatinny rail on the lower side for even more equipment.

It feartures a completely overworked reinforced body to withstand the much bigger drag.

A completely new designed trigger system, capable of holding such a high pull on the string.

I also added a simple and easy loading tool built in the crossbow for easy and fast reloading.

There are two sort of bow arms in the download available. One " average" which is more than enough powerfull, but there is also a "very strong" version with even stronger draw.

I had a lot of fail and error, bow arms breaking on me, pulleyes turning off its mount and so on.

It took many hours and test until I had a stable build ( which can still break at any point, you never know. Always keep in mind that temperature plays a big role in filaments, so when you take this crossbow out in winder the arms could snapp imidiately on first reload, the other way around if it is very hot outside the bow arms will not feature the same kind of power they would normally have in a more average tempered enviroment) The best results I had with PLA, its stiff and doesnt loose strength when bended, but it also broke the easiest after reaching the edge of PLAs " break point". ABS was ok to but I would still go with PLA.

Seriously this crossbow is so damn awesome I cant say thanks enough to william sharing this awesome piece of craftmanship!

Also keep in mind that at this point this is no kids toy anymore so use it responsible and under the same terms William shared his design with the world

NEVER HARM HUMANS OR ANIMALS with this Crossbow!!!!

I changed the design and build so you dont need those special threaded nuts you normaly have to melt into the printed design. Common screws will do the Trick.

Also a little bit of hammering and bending a 4mm Metal Rod is needed. ( I used brass) but you can use almost any type of metal as long its 4mm in diameter and a stable rod.

!!TIP!!
I had a ton of problem working those brass rods in shape, brass is very bridle and it broke on me like 20 times. User Mussy gave me a great tip, use a Bunsen burner and heat it up until the flame on the brass rod starts to change its color to orange/red. Let it cool down and then start to hammer and bend it, now it should not break!

The crossbow darts I made out of chopsticks, they are super cheap and work like a charm.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AgBtlTmWMSY&feature=youtu.be
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AJP_QvrOyOg&feature=youtu.be
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nCuEetluErM&feature=youtu.be

Things you will need for this build:

Some M3 and M4 hex inbus screws + nuts + washer ( look on the pictures to figure out how much of which sort)
4mm Brass Rod
M4 Thread cutter
Superglue
Wire ( best would be kevlar)
Rubberbands
chopsticks
Tape

Printer:

custom Delta

Resolution:

0,25 /0,30

Infill:

30-100%

Notes:

Some Parts of this build have to be printed with 100% infill so those parts are not going to break under high load:
The Crossbow Arms 100% infill
Trigger parts 100%infill
Crossbow Arms Mounts ( upper and lower side) 100% infill
Pulleyes (all parts) 100% infill
The rest I did with 30%infill but about 2mm Wall thickness.

I made everything in PLA exept the main body, it was printed in ABS because it feartures better mechanical features when it comes to turn screws into it.

description.text:
Double Direct Drive solution for the Hypercube Evo using a Nimble C/C and a Chimera/Cyclops.
Now you can use the Chimera/Cyclops with a direct drive without the usual weight penalties. This makes for a light and smooth working print head on your HEVO.

The Chimera and the Nimble C/C are bolted together clamping the mount. The mount has two supporting plates that hold the Chimera steady.

Edit: Added Version 2 mount as well. This one has a rails system on the side for the BL Touch mount that I used in the Single mount. The rails system makes it possible to us the BL Touch for the E3D V6 and for the Volcano hot end. Also included are the longer air ducts underneath to compensate for the 9 mm longer hot end.

Edit 2: Added a new Upper fan shroud to fit with the new Dual Nimble adapter. It is called Upper fan shroud V2

The STL models are checked and optimised. The parts that need a different orientation to print properly are rotated to the preferred printing position.

The Nimble Extruder

With an installed weight of less than 27 grams on your carriage/effector the Zesty Nimble is smallest and lightest extruder you can buy, it has ample torque and can be mounted in multiple orientations.

The Nimble is available from Zesty Technology.

description.text:
Hack-A-Day created these designs for a sabot system for Red Bull cans for our entry into the Red Bull Creation contest.  
It allows cans to be fired from our pneumatic cannon, dubbed the High Velocity Beverage Delivery System.
Each sabot also has attachments for a parachute and an LED (for night launches).

1: Print one each of the can top, can bottom, and Hack-a-Day logo.
2: Attach two rubber bands to each of the loops in the can bottom
3: Drill holes in the bottom of the can bottom piece and back of HaD logo for the LED.
4: Make an LED throwie with a 10mm LED by placing the LED leads through the holes you just drilled, and taping a coin cell battery across the leads so the LED lights up.
5: Glue the HaD logo over the LED on the bottom.
6: Put a small Red Bull can in the can bottom, place the can top on the can, and attach the rubber bands so that each pair of rubber bands is hooked to the hooks in the can top that are two spots to either side of the loop in the can bottom that the rubber bands are hooked to.
7: Drill holes and attach a hexagonal, 33 inch diameter parachute to the can top.
8: Fold up parachute and wrap its cords around itself.
9: Place can in High Velocity Beverage Distribution System, or throw can high in the air. Parachute will open, and beverage will return safely to earth.

title: Teal Sport Mars Mini Parachute Cover

description.text:
I figure a $500 drone is worthy of a decent parachute. This cover is designed to fit a Mars Mini v2 chute. There's a small cutout to run the wiring from the chute's servo under the cover. As far as I know, the Teal Sport can't directly trigger the chute's servo, but a small additional board could siphon power and handle an additional, emergency communication line.

The Mars Mini is spring-loaded and should safely fire between the rear props, but should the chute be necessary, I think the risk of striking some cheap props is the least of our concern.
